awaii in 1848 as an ABCFM missionary and served there until his death in Honolulu in 1880. He named his children for ABCFM colleagues: Juliette Cooke Dwight (for Juliette Montague Cooke, ABCFM missionary) and Samuel Castle Dwight (for Samuel Northrup Castle, ABCFM lay agent). His branch of the Hooker tree ends in Hawaii."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lived alongside John Dominis in Honolulu's missionary circle","body":"Samuel Gelston Dwight died in Honolulu in August 1880 as a prominent figure in the same small missionary-connected elite as John Owen Dominis — the man born in 1832 at Reverend Andrew Yates's Schenectady home, whose wife Hannah Allin Hooker was a seventh-generation descendant of Thomas Hooker. Dwight named his daughter Juliette Cooke Dwight for Juliette Montague Cooke, co-founder of the Royal School in Honolulu — the very school next to which young Dominis first encountered the royal children, setting in motion his courtship of the future Queen Liliʻuokalani."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"I00899","display_label":"Dominis born at Yates's home; Dwight knew him in Honolulu","link_text":"Reverend Andrew Yates"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"X02833","display_label":"Both lived in Honolulu's missionary elite for decades","link_text":"John Owen Dominis"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Gelston Dwight","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Dwight","middle_name":"Gelston","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://www.wikitree.com/photo.php/9/97/Dwight-779.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"samuel-dwight-1815"},"X00772":{"id":"X00772","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":f